      Non-pro rata uptiering
   =20
 =20

I have a schematic model of modern distressed debt that goes like this:
=09A company has $100 of debt outstanding.=09It goes to the holders of 51% =
of the debt and says =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll give you a little bonus if you =
agree to stiff the other 49%.=E2=80=9D=09The company pays those holders bac=
k with a little bonus, maybe paying them $60 for their $51 of debt.=09In re=
turn, they vote to amend the terms of the debt to say that the=C2=A0other=
=C2=A0guys =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ones with 49% of the debt =E2=80=94=C2=A0get =
zero.=09Net, the majority holders get $9 extra, and the company saves $40 b=
y stiffing the minority holders.

This model is technically incorrect, as essentially no debt contracts allow=
 a majority vote to=C2=A0cancel=C2=A0a minority=E2=80=99s debts. But this m=
odel is universally useful, because essentially every debt contract allows =
a majority (or supermajority) vote to do=C2=A0something unpleasant=C2=A0to =
the minority: remove covenants, strip collateral, allow more senior debt, s=
omething. And so companies regularly strike deals with some holders of thei=
r debt, deals that (1) give those holders some goodies, (2) give the compan=
y some goodies (new money, maturity extensions, etc.) and (3) generate thos=
e goodies by taking value from the other holders.
These days these transactions tend to be described by the generic name =E2=
=80=9Cliability management exercises,=E2=80=9D or LMEs, but they also have =
specific names. Here are Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0Reshmi Basu and Claire Bo=
ston on=C2=A0non-pro rata uptiering:

It=E2=80=99s the latest in a wave of maneuvers =E2=80=94 often masked by ba=
nal legalistic terminology =E2=80=94 that distressed funds and others manag=
ing billions of dollars are deploying to clean up at their rivals=E2=80=99 =
expense. The new deals are typically structured as below-par debt exchanges=
 at a variety of different price points. Creditors that negotiate the propo=
sals usually provide new money and receive the smallest haircuts on their h=
oldings. Those that choose not to participate risk being stripped of their =
collateral and covenants, while also getting pushed down the repayment prio=
rity line. =E2=80=A6
Among the most controversial recent transactions was a proposal from=C2=A0B=
ain Capital=E2=80=99s Apex Tool Group. Creditors including=C2=A0Angelo Gord=
on & Co.,=C2=A0Anchorage Capital Group=C2=A0and Elliott Investment Manageme=
nt-backed=C2=A0Elmwood Asset Management=C2=A0took part in a deal that saw t=
hem swap first-lien debt into a newly created higher-priority term loan =E2=
=80=94 which is effectively second in line =E2=80=94 at around 90 cents on =
the dollar. Those that weren=E2=80=99t part of the negotiating group could =
exchange their debt for a mix of the new loan and a lower-ranking obligatio=
n at roughly 73 cents.=C2=A0
The value of the original debt=C2=A0plunged=C2=A0following the exchange off=
er, and some creditors=C2=A0banded together=C2=A0with lawyers to assess the=
ir options. But ultimately, holders of more than 90% of the company=E2=80=
=99s first-lien loan agreed to the deal. Not going along with the plan woul=
d have seen them fall well back in the line for repayment. ...
=E2=80=9CThe practical problem is that many lenders are concerned about the=
 liability management exercises =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s almost secondary to =
how the business is performing,=E2=80=9D said David Orlofsky of global cons=
ulting firm AlixPartners. =E2=80=9CThe fear of being left behind is now cau=
sing some lenders who don=E2=80=99t like the proposed LME transaction to su=
pport it anyway. They would rather be part of it than being left out and ad=
versely impacted.=E2=80=9D

Generically you might imagine that it would be a bad thing, for a distresse=
d company, if all of its creditors are viciously competitive sharp-elbowed =
fighters. But if you can get them to fight against=C2=A0each other, then yo=
u can take some value for yourself.

