<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Destiny</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDQtMDgvcHVibGljLW1hcmtldHMtYXJlLXRoZS1uZXctcHJpdmF0ZS1t=
YXJrZXRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MDkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3N=
vdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB417cd035" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked yesterday</a> about the =
Destiny Tech100 fund, but I worry that I did not sufficiently emphasize how=
 wild it is. Here is what it is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A guy named Sohail Prasad=C2=A0raised=
 a fund to invest in hot private technology companies=C2=A0like SpaceX and=
=C2=A0Stripe.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It currently owns sh=
ares in about 23 private companies, worth about $52.6 million.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Two weeks ago, it went public by =
a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34979401.287353/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDM5NzQvMDAwMTU3NTg=
3MjIzMDAxOTI0L2VzMDg2XzQyNGIzLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeaf395bb" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">direct listing</a> on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker DXYZ=
, so that now anyone can buy or sell shares of the fund on the exchange.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is an idea that lots of people have had: =
Wouldn=E2=80=99t it be nice to give ordinary investors access to hot startu=
ps?=C2=A0DXYZ is=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cproviding everyday investors access to these=
 private market leaders for the first time,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZXN0aW55Lnh5=
ei90ZWNoMTAw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB056190e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">its website says</a=
>. The New York Times said last week:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is a problem that has vexed retail investor=
s for years, as start-ups like Stripe, SpaceX and OpenAI soar to enormous v=
aluations in the private market. Only so-called accredited investors with a=
 high net worth are allowed to invest in private tech start-ups. By the tim=
e the companies go public a decade or more after they started, their growth=
 has often slowed and their valuations are high.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A new fund, Destiny Tech100, is trying to chan=
ge that with a novel solution.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay. But here is what is wild about it:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The portfolio is worth $52.6 million,=
 give or take, or about $4.84 per share. That value is uncertain (it is bas=
ed on subjective valuations, as the portfolio companies by definition do no=
t trade publicly) and a bit stale (as of December), but it=E2=80=99s probab=
ly close enough.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The stock opened,=
 in the direct listing, at $8.25 per share. It closed yesterday at $99.79 p=
er share, for a market capitalization of almost $1.1 billion. (It=E2=80=99s=
 down=C2=A0today.)=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">That is a=
=C2=A0<em>1,961% premium </em>to net asset value.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That just seems very high? It is nice, in theo=
ry, to say that this fund gives ordinary investors access to startups befor=
e they go public and =E2=80=9Ctheir growth has often slowed and their valua=
tions are high.=E2=80=9D But with that premium, this fund gives ordinary in=
vestors access to startups at <em>20 times their current valuation</em>.=C2=
=A0DXYZ=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34979=
401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly9kZXN0aW55Lnh5ei90ZWNoMTAw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC05=
6190e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">advertises:</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9CFor many companies at the pre=
-IPO stage, there may be the potential to yield a 10-50x return.=E2=80=9D<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But a 10x return on the <em>entire portfolio </em>would be a=C2=
=A0<em>disaster=C2=A0</em>for DXYZ investors, since then the portfolio woul=
d be worth something like $580 million,=C2=A0<em>way less=C2=A0</em>than it=
s current market value. As I wrote yesterday, =E2=80=9Cif each of this fund=
=E2=80=99s holdings goes up 1,000% by the time they go public, people who b=
ought into the fund today will=C2=A0<em>lose money</em>.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or to put it another way, if you buy shares in=
 DXYZ, you are getting almost no exposure to Stripe and SpaceX; you are mos=
tly getting exposure to DXYZ=E2=80=99s own premium. More than 90% of the va=
lue of the stock is premium; the portfolio is an afterthought.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What do you make of this? We do live in an age=
 of meme stocks; I talk all the time around here about stocks that trade at=
 prices that seem to be disconnected from their fundamental value. =E2=80=
=9CThis is a way for ordinary investors to get access to hot startups=E2=80=
=9D is a good=C2=A0<em>meme</em>, whether or not it is true as a matter of =
arithmetic. If the only publicly traded way to get access to hot startups h=
as $50 million worth of hot startups, there=E2=80=99s no law of nature that=
 prevents it from trading at $1 billion. =E2=80=9CThe public listing of DXY=
Z has become a cultural moment that=E2=80=99s taken on a life of its own,=
=E2=80=9D Prasad told me by email, which is a nice way to say it=E2=80=99s =
a meme stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, what do I always say about =
meme-stock companies? I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwOTI0=
X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3R=
lcm09MjQwNDA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd05e=
2297" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">say</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDEtMDYvdGVzbGEta2VwdC1idXN5LWluLTIwMjA_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQwOTI0X01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jQwNDA5JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8d20179e" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">they</a> <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3=
4979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjAtMDYtMTIvaWYteW91LXdhbnQtaGVydHotaGF2ZS1zb21lLWhlcnR6P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MDk=
yNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV=
90ZXJtPTI0MDQwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6=
497ed76" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;">should</a> sell <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDcvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNvbGQtc29tZS1zdG9jaz9jbXB=
pZD1CQkQwNDA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2=
xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA0MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8=
524a319a23cB7f9cd416" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">stock</a>. That trade actually works rather n=
icely here. DXYZ is an exchange-listed closed-end fund; it is not an exchan=
ge-traded fund. In an ETF, certain investors (=E2=80=9Cauthorized participa=
nts=E2=80=9D) can create and redeem shares of the fund: They can deliver a =
basket of the underlying portfolio to the fund sponsor and get back ETF sha=
res, or they can deliver ETF shares to the sponsor and get back the underly=
ing portfolio. This creates an arbitrage: If the ETF trades at a premium to=
 its net asset value, arbitrageurs will buy the underlying assets, deliver =
them to the sponsor, get back ETF shares and sell them to capture the premi=
um.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tr=
ansparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> (And vice versa, if it trades at a discount.) This drives down the pri=
ce of the ETF (and drives up the price of the underlying assets), closing t=
he premium. In liquid markets, this normally keeps the price of the ETF in =
line with the value of its portfolio.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That doesn=E2=80=99t work here, because DXYZ i=
s a closed-end fund, not an ETF. Investors cannot create or redeem shares; =
they can=E2=80=99t put money in or take money out. The reason for that is p=
retty obvious: DXYZ doesn=E2=80=99t own a portfolio of liquid publicly trad=
ed stocks. It owns stakes in private companies; each investment has to be i=
ndividually negotiated, and they can=E2=80=99t necessarily be sold quickly,=
 or at all. DXYZ=E2=80=99s shares trade publicly and liquidly, but its unde=
rlying assets do not.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still the basic idea still works: DXYZ should =
sell stock!<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> So much stock. It should sell stock to the public at a 1,000% premium =
to its net asset value or whatever, and then use the money to invest in mor=
e stakes in more private companies. If you do enough of that, then:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You collapse the premium: Selling sto=
ck and buying the underlying assets will move the price of the stock closer=
 to the price of the underlying assets.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">You average into the valuation. Right now DXYZ has, call it, $1 billi=
on of stock and a $50 million portfolio, a 1,900% premium. If it sells anot=
her $1 billion of stock, and invests the proceeds into new private-company =
stakes, it will have $2 billion of stock and a $1.05 billion portfolio, a 9=
0% premium.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Progress!=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are some limits on this: DXYZ doesn=E2=
=80=99t just have to raise the money; it also has to deploy it, to find goo=
d private companies (or their shareholders) who are willing to sell it shar=
es at reasonable valuations.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that is a problem for any venture capital =
fund, and DXYZ is in some ways in a very nice position. For one thing, regu=
lar venture capital funds <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9leGl0cy1hcmU=
