X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDQwOSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
mZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc598dce3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s David Vo=
reacos and Chris Dolmetsch report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A jailed trader accused of stealing $110 milli=
on on the Mango Markets exchange faces a criminal trial this week that will=
 test the reach of a US crackdown on cryptocurrencies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Prosecutors charged Avraham Eisenberg with man=
ipulating Mango Markets futures contracts on Oct. 11, 2022, to boost the pr=
ice of swaps by 1,300% in 20 minutes. He then =E2=80=9Cborrowed=E2=80=9D fr=
om the exchange against the inflated value of those contracts, a move the g=
overnment claims was a theft. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eisenberg, a self-described =E2=80=9Capplied g=
ame theorist,=E2=80=9D claims his actions weren=E2=80=99t theft at all. Rat=
her, he says, he legally exploited a weakness in the decentralized finance =
application. The trial will apparently be the first time a US criminal jury=
 will weigh what type of =E2=80=9CDeFi=E2=80=9D transactions are legal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the crypto world, where digital blockchains=
 govern who owns what, the virtual ecosystem is built around the notion tha=
t =E2=80=9Ccode is law.=E2=80=9D It means that if something isn=E2=80=99t e=
xplicitly forbidden by terms of a crypto platform, then government can=E2=
=80=99t intercede. But prosecutors say those rules can=E2=80=99t protect tr=
aders against possible criminal charges for market manipulation or fraud.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt touches on the big argument within=
 crypto =E2=80=94 is code law?=E2=80=9D said Chris Janczewski, head of glob=
al investigations at TRM Labs. =E2=80=9CIf the code allows somebody to do t=
hat, does the actual law? Obviously, the government took a different approa=
ch that code is not law. Just because there is an opportunity to exploit it=
 does not mean that it=E2=80=99s legal.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, <em>some </em>people in crypto clearly b=
elieve that =E2=80=9Ccode is law,=E2=80=9D and that if an =E2=80=9Capplied =
game theorist=E2=80=9D can find a flaw in market structure and exploit it f=
or $110 million, then (1) good for him and (2) that will create incentives =
to fix the market structure.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But some other people in crypto clearly=C2=A0<=
em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>see it that way, and want a more regulated marke=
t, in part to protect them from mistakes but also because they want=C2=A0<e=
m>broader crypto adoption</em>, and the very obvious lesson from 100 years =
of US stock markets is that, when people perceive a market to be fair and o=
rderly and regulated and safe, they are more likely to invest in it. There =
is no monolithic =E2=80=9Ccrypto world=E2=80=9D that believes that manipula=
tion is fine, and that is now up against meddling US prosecutors who disagr=
ee. There are intra-crypto disagreements about whether Eisenberg is a hero =
(or, at least, a charming rogue) or a villain.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am just saying that you could resolve those =
disagreements by letting everyone go their separate ways. Have Nice Crypto =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0probably the bulk of it? =E2=80=94=C2=A0where manipulation i=
s disfavored and government intervention is, at least in theory, welcomed. =
And have Fun Crypto for the applied game theorists to play their games agai=
nst each other. Have a market that makes it explicit, in advance, on the we=
b page, =E2=80=9CAnything that you can do on our platform is allowed, and i=
f the results are absurd then that is fun for you and bad for someone else,=
 you=E2=80=99re on notice!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that would really=C2=A0<=
em>keep out=C2=A0</em>federal prosecutors =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=E2=80=99re fr=
ee to argue that something allowed by the explicit rules of the market was =
nonetheless fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it might help? As it is, actual crypto=
 lives mostly in ambiguity, where some people think that code is law and ot=
hers think that law is law.</p>
