<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMDcvZGlzdHJlc3NlZC1kZWJ0LWRlYWwtbWFrZXMtcGVvcG=
xlLW1hZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDA5MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA0MDkmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45e37b7d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">schematic model of modern distre=
ssed debt</a> that goes like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company has $100 of debt outstandin=
g.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It goes to the holders of 51% o=
f the debt and says =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll give you a little bonus if you a=
gree to stiff the other 49%.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The company pays those holders back with a little bonus, maybe paying t=
hem $60 for their $51 of debt.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In =
return, they vote to amend the terms of the debt to say that the=C2=A0<em>o=
ther=C2=A0</em>guys =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ones with 49% of the debt =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0get zero.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Net, the majority =
holders get $9 extra, and the company saves $40 by stiffing the minority ho=
lders.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This model is technically incorrect, as essent=
ially no debt contracts allow a majority vote to=C2=A0<em>cancel=C2=A0</em>=
a minority=E2=80=99s debts. But this model is universally useful, because e=
ssentially every debt contract allows a majority (or supermajority) vote to=
 do=C2=A0<em>something unpleasant=C2=A0</em>to the minority: remove covenan=
ts, strip collateral, allow more senior debt, something. And so companies r=
egularly strike deals with some holders of their debt, deals that (1) give =
those holders some goodies, (2) give the company some goodies (new money, m=
aturity extensions, etc.) and (3) generate those goodies by taking value fr=
om the other holders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These days these transactions tend to be descr=
ibed by the generic name =E2=80=9Cliability management exercises,=E2=80=9D =
or LMEs, but they also have specific names. Here are Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0Reshmi Basu and Claire Boston on=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/34979401.287353/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5j=
b20vYmFua3J1cHRjeS1sYXcvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtZmluZC1pdHMtaGl0LWZpcnN0LW9yLWdldC1=
odXJ0LWluLWRpc3RyZXNzZWQtZmlnaHRz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f53192e" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
">non-pro rata uptiering</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s the latest in a wave of maneuvers=
 =E2=80=94 often masked by banal legalistic terminology =E2=80=94 that dist=
ressed funds and others managing billions of dollars are deploying to clean=
 up at their rivals=E2=80=99 expense. The new deals are typically structure=
d as below-par debt exchanges at a variety of different price points. Credi=
tors that negotiate the proposals usually provide new money and receive the=
 smallest haircuts on their holdings. Those that choose not to participate =
risk being stripped of their collateral and covenants, while also getting p=
ushed down the repayment priority line. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the most controversial recent transactio=
ns was a proposal from=C2=A0Bain Capital=E2=80=99s Apex Tool Group. Credito=
rs including=C2=A0Angelo Gordon &amp; Co.,=C2=A0Anchorage Capital Group=C2=
=A0and Elliott Investment Management-backed=C2=A0Elmwood Asset Management=
=C2=A0took part in a deal that saw them swap first-lien debt into a newly c=
reated higher-priority term loan =E2=80=94 which is effectively second in l=
ine =E2=80=94 at around 90 cents on the dollar. Those that weren=E2=80=99t =
part of the negotiating group could exchange their debt for a mix of the ne=
w loan and a lower-ranking obligation at roughly 73 cents.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The value of the original debt=C2=A0plunged=C2=
=A0following the exchange offer, and some creditors=C2=A0banded together=C2=
=A0with lawyers to assess their options. But ultimately, holders of more th=
an 90% of the company=E2=80=99s first-lien loan agreed to the deal. Not goi=
ng along with the plan would have seen them fall well back in the line for =
repayment. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe practical problem is that many le=
nders are concerned about the liability management exercises =E2=80=94 it=
=E2=80=99s almost secondary to how the business is performing,=E2=80=9D sai=
d David Orlofsky of global consulting firm AlixPartners. =E2=80=9CThe fear =
of being left behind is now causing some lenders who don=E2=80=99t like the=
 proposed LME transaction to support it anyway. They would rather be part o=
f it than being left out and adversely impacted.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Generically you might imagine that it would be=
 a bad thing, for a distressed company, if all of its creditors are vicious=
ly competitive sharp-elbowed fighters. But if you can get them to fight aga=
inst=C2=A0<em>each other</em>, then you can take some value for yourself.</=
p>
